# Flint — Git Workflow

## Branch per meaningful chunk

For every **meaningful implementation chunk** (feature, fix, refactor, or vertical slice — not drive-by edits):

1. **Start on `main`** (or rebase onto latest `main` first).
2. **Create a branch** before writing code:
   - `feature/<short-kebab-description>` — new capability
   - `fix/<short-kebab-description>` — bug fix
   - `chore/<short-kebab-description>` — tooling, deps, CI only
   - `docs/<short-kebab-description>` — README / comments only (if `docs/` is tracked elsewhere)
3. Keep the branch **focused**: one logical change set; split if it grows past ~1 reviewable PR.

Examples: `feature/audio-pipeline-vad`, `fix/whisper-model-path`, `chore/ci-rust-cache`.

## During the session

- Commit on the **feature branch**, not on `main`.
- Commit when the user asks, or when a coherent unit of work is done.
- Messages: concise, imperative, explain **why** (e.g. `Add PipeWire loopback capture for system audio`).
- Never commit secrets (`.env`, keys, `credentials.json`).
- Never use `--no-verify` unless the user explicitly requests it.

## End of session

Before finishing agent work on a chunk:

1. `git status` — ensure intended files are staged; no secrets.
2. Commit any remaining work on the branch.
3. **Push the branch**: `git push -u origin HEAD`
4. Tell the user the branch name and that they can open a PR to `main` (use `gh pr create` only if asked).

Do **not** push directly to `main` for feature work unless the user explicitly asks.

## Initial / repo setup

- Remote: `https://github.com/abzanganeh/flint.git`
- `docs/` is gitignored (local design docs only); do not add it to commits.

## What counts as a “meaningful chunk”

| Yes — new branch | No — stay on current branch |
|------------------|-------------------------------|
| New module or panel | Typo in comment |
| New Tauri command + event contract | Formatting-only |
| Prompt + orchestrator behavior change | Single-line fix in same PR scope |
| Migration or RLS change | Follow-up commit same session, same PR |

When unsure, prefer a **new branch** over mixing unrelated changes on one branch.
